		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.fusionbposervices.com/blog/?p=6220</guid>
				<description><![CDATA[What makes the fourth Saturday of November so special? Is it the opulence of food? Is it the fact that the holidays are coming closer? Or is it the bliss of togetherness and the gratitude for having good company? We think it’s the last one &#8211; after all, the holiday is called thanksgiving. It’s time [&#8230;]]]></description>
								<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>What makes the fourth Saturday of November so special? Is it the opulence of food? Is it the fact that the holidays are coming closer? Or is it the bliss of togetherness and the gratitude for having good company? We think it’s the last one &#8211; after all, the holiday is called thanksgiving.</p>
<p>It’s time to give thanks to every person who made your world a better place with their presence. The same thing applies for businesses as well. They should give thanks to every person who helped the business rise to success i.e. its employees, vendors, investors and most importantly, its customers, without whom, there won’t be a business.</p>
<p>But just merely saying a thank you or sending a thanksgiving themed mail to your customers won’t cut it this Thanksgiving. With the competition getting steeper by the day, it’s time your actions start speaking louder than your words. Make the customers feel special and appreciated, and, thank them earnestly for their continued support. Here are a few tips for practicing what you preach.</p>
<ol>
<li>
<h3>Customize your email</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p>We know it is hard to write personalized emails to each and every one of your customers. But you can at least customize your emails targeting your brand loyalists who have stuck with you for a long period of time. They would love to know once in a while that the brand they love has high esteem for them.</p>
<ol start="2">
<li>
<h3>Offer free service</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Track the last purchase of each customer and mail them a promo code for free servicing on the same or offer them a discount on its accessories. It will improve their brand experience and turn them into loyal customers.</p>
<ol start="3">
<li>
<h3>Do not make them wait</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p>We know holidays can be hectic, especially for the customer service department. But when a customer calls your customer service number, he or she is not in the mood for waiting in a long call queue, they can use that time to do something else. Don’t keep them waiting. Hire more customer service agents or seek the help of <strong>a renowned call center </strong>well in advance. Thanksgiving is just the beginning or a long shopping season and you need to be on your toes.</p>
<ol start="4">
<li>
<h3>Ask them for feedback</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p>A busy season is no excuse for delivering poor customer experience. And even if there’s an occasional setback, make sure to amend your ways. Ask the customers what can make your product or service better and thank them for their feedback. Work on Improving things and let them know that you are working on it.</p>
<ol start="5">
<li>
<h3>Keep your promises</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Don’t just give your customers false hope that things will be better if you can’t make it better. Giving false hope and failing to deliver are a deadly combo and the surest way to your doom.</p>
<ol start="6">
<li>
<h3>Keep practicing what you preach</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p>‘Thank You’ is too important and too powerful a tool to confine to just a single holiday. Keep thanking your customers by making every effort possible to make their experience with you worthwhile. We already know customer experience is one of the most vital factors that can turn a first time customer into a loyal one.</p>
<h3><strong>Happy Thanksgiving from all of us at Fusion.</strong></h3>
]]></content:encoded>
